Ingest_LDD.name: DART Mission
Ingest_LDD.comment: This is the DART Mission local data dictionary setup file to be run on the PDS4 lddtool in order to create a local data dictionary.

DD_Attribute.name: acquisition_time
DD_Attribute.definition: DRACO image time of validity (TOV) in integer seconds, in spacecraft clock notation. This is the time for which the GNC attitude data is valid. See the DRACO SIS for calculation of this value.

DD_Attribute.name: badpix_invalidation_mode
DD_Attribute.definition: Flags whether bad pixels identified by the on-board bad pixel map are invalidated by SMARTNAV. When invalidated the pixels in the raw image are set to the SNAVFLAG value in the raw fits header.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: Bad pixels identified by bad pixel map are invalidated by SMARTNAV
Bad pixel map is not used to invalidate pixels.

DD_Attribute.name: binning
DD_Attribute.definition: Identifies whether pixel binning was applied to generate the image.

DD_Attribute.name: calibration_file
DD_Attribute.definition: Name of calibration table file provided by SMART Nav to the spacecraft for use when onboard calibration is applied. Data values from this file are added back to the downloaded image if applied to the image on board. The file is stored on-board as a .mat file, but the same data values are archived in the DRACO Calibrated Data Collection as a .fits file. The archived filename is the same as the base filename shown here with the '.fits' extension.

DD_Attribute.name: detector_temp
DD_Attribute.definition: Instrument detector temperature for LICIACube. The container class identifies whether it is for LUKE or LEIA.

DD_Attribute.name: detector1_temp
DD_Attribute.definition: DRACO detector temperature sensor 1.

DD_Attribute.name: detector2_temp
DD_Attribute.definition: DRACO detector temperature sensor 2.

DD_Attribute.name: fpe_temp
DD_Attribute.definition: DRACO FPE board temperature.

DD_Attribute.name: liciacube_calibration_file
DD_Attribute.definition: Name of calibration table file used by LICIACube calibration pipeline.

DD_Attribute.name: onboard_cal
DD_Attribute.definition: Defines whether calibration table was applied to the DRACO image onboard the DART spacecraft prior to downlink.

DD_Attribute.name: mission_phase
DD_Attribute.definition: The mission_phase identifies the time period within the mission.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: The prelaunch phase refers to the period of software development and testing of the data processing pipeline, before launch. Data products generated during this phase include calibration files created during the ground testing of the instrument as well as data products created for peer review.
The commissioning phase lasts for TBD days after launch. Images acquired during this phase include calibrations and functional testing for DRACO to ensure proper operations.

The cruise phase begins after the commissioning phase and runs until the beginning of teh approach phase. Images acquired during this phase are used for several purposes, including for Optical navigation (OpNav), testing of SMART Nav algorithms, and star calibrations to characterize distortion and responsivity.

The approach phase begins begins when the Didymos system is first acquired by DRACO, ~30 days before impact, and extends until the terminal phase begins. During this phase, DRACO acquires a long-range suite of observations where the Didymos system is mostly not resolvable. Light curve information complementary to ground-based observations will be extracted from these images.

The terminal phase begins with the initiation of DART's autonomous navigation, ~4 h prior to impact, and extends until the final phase begins. During this phase, the separation between Didymos and Dimorphos can be resolved, and DRACO images support both autonomous navigation (via Smart Nav algorithms) and characterization of Didymos and Dimorphos. The final image to contain both members of the system will be acquired ~4 minutes before impact, at a scale of ~7m. By the end of this phase, images will be obtained of Dimorphos that have a 2 x 2 binned pixel scale of ~3.5m.

The final phase comprises the last ~4 min of the DART mission. During this phase, all DRACO images will be devoted to characterization of Dimorphos, as autonomous navingation will have been completed. In the baseline trajectory at ~20s (TBR after launch) prior to impact, DRACO achieves its requirement to image Dimorphos at a pixel scale of 66 cm. Higher resolution images will continue to be acquired in the final seconds of DART spacecraft operations, which end upon impact.

DD_Attribute.name: exposure_time
DD_Attribute.definition: Image exposure time in seconds.

DD_Attribute.name: gain
DD_Attribute.definition: Defines the detector gain setting used. The container class identifies whether this is for the DRACO, LUKE, or LEIA detectors.

DD_Attribute.name: bad_image
DD_Attribute.definition: Identifies image whose image data and FPE metadata are not reliable and should not be used for analysis.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: This is a bad image. Should not be used for analysis
This is not a bad image. Can be used for analysis.

DD_Attribute.name: observation_type
DD_Attribute.definition: Describes the purpose for which the image was taken.

DD_Attribute.name: imaging_mode
DD_Attribute.definition: The imaging_mode defines the shutter readout mode of the DRACO detector.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: In global shutter readout mode the entire detector integrates over the same time period. Global shutter images will have higher noise relative to rolling shutter images, but no spatial distortion beyond that caused by the optics (less than or equal to 0.1%).

In rolling shutter mode each row of the detector integrates over the same amount of time, but the exact moment in time captured by each line is different (i.e., each line begins integrating by one line time after the previous line).

DD_Attribute.name: lineread
DD_Attribute.definition: Defines the time it takes to readout a single line of the detector in microsec/line.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_time
DD_Attribute.definition: Defines the global readout time in microseconds.

DD_Attribute.name: pix_delay
DD_Attribute.definition: Delay between sequential pixels in line in nanoseconds.

DD_Attribute.name: current_analog_reset_supply
DD_Attribute.definition: Current for detector analog reset supply.

DD_Attribute.name: current_18vd_supply
DD_Attribute.definition: Current for detector 1.8VD supply.

DD_Attribute.name: current_33va_supply
DD_Attribute.definition: Current for detector 3.3VA supply.

DD_Attribute.name: current_33vd_supply
DD_Attribute.definition: Current for detector 3.3VD supply.

DD_Attribute.name: liciacube_sclk_image_time
DD_Attribute.definition: Start of image capture time in spacecraft clock notation. Numeric number preceding the decimal point is integer seconds. Numeric number after the decimal point is subsecond clock ticks, where each tick represents TBD microseconds.

DD_Attribute.name: correct_image_time
DD_Attribute.definition: LICIACube keyword containing the UTC Time at mid exposure as measured from the effective time of acquisition. This is the reference time used to generate the SPICE derived geometry values in the LICIACube fits header

DD_Attribute.name: soc_acquisition_time
DD_Attribute.definition: DRACO image time of validity calculated by the SOC based on FPE_SEC and FPE_SBSS in the fits header. Represented as ascii integers in "sec:subsecond_ticks" where "sec" is the spacecraft clock counter in whole seconds since epoch and "subsecond_ticks" are in spacecraft clock subsecond clock ticks. Each tick represents 1/50,000 second. Example: "298271898:2345"

DD_Attribute.name: test_pattern
DD_Attribute.definition: If present it describes the test pattern in the image. If there is no test pattern then this keyword will not appear in the label.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: The image contains a static horizontal gradient test pattern.
The image contains a dynamic horizontal gradient test pattern. It is dynamic in the sense that the pixel values created by this test pattern vary from image to image.
The image contains a two-box test pattern.
The image contains a uniform gray image.

DD_Attribute.name: test_temp
DD_Attribute.definition: Nominal temperature for the test sequence used to generate the data product. Reported by the calibration files, i.e. flat fields, bias, and dark images.

DD_Attribute.name: window_x_start
DD_Attribute.definition: Column where window starts with respect to a LICIACUBE image array. The container identifies whether this is the LEIA or LUKE image array. For LEIA this is a 2048 x 2048 image, for LUKE it is a 1088 x 2048 image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window_x_end
DD_Attribute.definition: Column where window ends with respect to a LICIACUBE image array. The container identifies whether this is the LEIA or LUKE image array. For LEIA this is a 2048 x 2048 image, for LUKE it is a 1088 x 2048 image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window_y_start
DD_Attribute.definition: Row where window starts with respect to a LICIACUBE image array. The container identifies whether this is the LEIA or LUKE image array. For LEIA this is a 2048 x 2048 image, for LUKE it is a 1088 x 2048 image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window_y_end
DD_Attribute.definition: Row where window ends with respect to a LICIACUBE image array. The container identifies whether this is the LEIA or LUKE image array. For LEIA this is a 2048 x 2048 image, for LUKE it is a 1088 x 2048 image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window2_x_start
DD_Attribute.definition: Starting column of windowed image data with respect to a 1024 x 1025 image array, where the top row of the array is the header row containing metadata associated with the image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Look at value of window2_x_end to determine whether windowing is applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window2_x_end
DD_Attribute.definition: Ending column of windowed image data with respect to a 1024 x 1025 image array, where the top row of the array is the header row containing metadata associated with the image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window2_y_start
DD_Attribute.definition: Starting row of windowed image data with respect to a 1024 x 1025 image array, where the top row of the array is the header row containing metadata associated with the image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Look at value of window2_y_end to determine whether windowing is applied.

DD_Attribute.name: window2_y_end
DD_Attribute.definition: Ending row of windowed image data with respect to a 1024 x 1025 image array, where the top row of the array is the header row containing metadata associated with the image. Upper left hand corner is coordinate 0,0. Set to -1 if windowing is not applied.

DD_Attribute.name: undo_onboard_cal
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether on-board calibration table was undone, ie. by adding it back to the image. NA if onboard_cal table was not applied to the image.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: Onboard calibration not applied to the image

DD_Attribute.name: bias_subtraction
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether bias subtraction step was done. If performed, then refer to the Reference_List in the XML for the LID of the bias file used. The bias subtraction file is also archived in the DRACO Calibrated Data Collection.

DD_Attribute.name: dark_subtraction
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether dark subtraction step was done. If performed then refer to the Reference_List in the XML for the LID of the dark file used. The dark subtraction file is also archived in the DRACO Calibrated Data Collection.

DD_Attribute.name: flatfield
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether flat field was applied. If performed then refer to the Reference_List in the XML for the LID of the flat field file used. The flat field file is also archived in the DRACO Calibrated Data Collection.

DD_Attribute.name: radiance_conversion
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether conversion to radiance was applied. If performed then refer to the the DRACO calibration pipeline description document for the steps performed to convert pixel values to electrons then from electrons to radiance. If performed then refer to the Reference_List in the XML for the LID of the lookup table used. The lookup table file is also archived in the DRACO Calibrated Data Collection.

DD_Attribute.name: ioverf_conversion
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether conversion to I/F was applied. If performed then refer to the DRACO calibraiton pipeline description document for the steps performed to convert pixel values to I/F. The F_SUN622 keyword in the fits header contains the solar flux at 622nm (the DRACO pivot wavelength) as well as the PHDIST and SHDIST keywords for the heliocentric distance to the primary and secondary bodies respectively.

DD_Class.name: DART_Parameters
DD_Class.definition: The DART_Parameters class is the superclass containing all DART mission data dictionary classes.

DD_Class.name: Time
DD_Class.definition: The Time class contains metadata describing different time components associated with the DART mission.

DD_Class.name: DRACO_Instrument_Attributes
DD_Class.definition: The DRACO_Instrument_Attributes class contains metadata associated with the DRACO Instrument.

DD_Class.name: LEIA_Instrument_Attributes
DD_Class.definition: The LEIA_Instrument_Attributes class contains metadata associated with the LEIA Instrument on the LICIACube spacecraft.

DD_Class.name: LUKE_Instrument_Attributes
DD_Class.definition: The LUKE_Instrument_Attributes class contains metadata associated with the LUKE Instrument on the LICIACube spacecraft.

DD_Class.name: DRACO_Data_Processing_Information
DD_Class.definition: The DRACO_data_processing_information class contains metadata describing the processing steps performed on the image. The processing steps are listed in the same order executed by the data processing pipeline
